<TEXT>
the emergence of neonazi 
groups and black leader nelson mandelas embrace of yasser arafat 
have frightened south africas jews who fear the country may be 
facing a wave of antisemitism 
south african jewish leaders are concerned south africas tense 
political situation is giving neonazi and other antisemitic 
groups more opportunity to operate and increase their support 
the south african government has expressed concern over a recent 
rash of incidents 
these extremist acts of desecration have no place in a 
civilized society foreign minister pik botha said in a statement 
swastika flags and antijewish slogans have become prominent at 
extreme rightwing rallies an israeli flag was burned at a 
rightwing meeting in pretoria in february and vandals left a 
severed pig head and a swastika on a synagogue door in johannesburg 
in march 
members of the neonazi afrikaner resistance movement wear khaki 
uniforms and insignia reminiscent of the stormtroopers of nazi 
germany antisemitic slogans and placards are becoming more common 
at the groups meetings 
south africas jewish community also was shocked when mandela 
embraced palestine liberation organization leader arafat in zambia 
mandela said his african national congress and the plo were allied 
freedom fighters 
told his action had worried south african jews mandela said it 
was too bad according to local press reports 
gerald leissner chairman of the south african jewish board of 
deputies said the antisemitic incidents were worrying we would 
like to live in a society in which there is no racial hatred 
unfortunately it seems these incidents are becoming more 
frequent he said 
the right wing has been gaining strength in south africa because 
of fears among some whites over the governments plan to end 
whiteminority rule and share political power with blacks 
while the main rightwing parties publicly denounce 
antisemitism some of their supporters have openly paraded with 
swastika flags more extreme rightist groups are attracting support 
and neonazi groups are starting to operate in the open according 
to jewish leaders 
aleck goldberg national executive director of the south african 
jewish board of deputies the main jewish leadership said the wave 
of antisemitic incidents had frightened many south african jews 
the nazis are crawling out of the woodwork he said in an 
interview up until now theyve been underground they havent 
come forward in the past 
goldberg said nazi groups were claiming that jews are part of a 
racial conspiracy to end whiteminority rule jews were being 
singled out because many are prominent liberals who have fought 
against apartheid he said 
the nazi groups appear small with no more than a few hundred 
supporters but jewish leaders want the government to take action 
to ensure they do not become a serious threat 
we would hope because of the inflamatory nature of what 
theyre doing that the authorities will take strong action against 
them goldberg said 
the jewish community also was worried about that black 
nationalist groups might be antisemitic jewish leaders did not 
see mandela as antisemitic but were worried about the ancs ties 
with the plo goldberg said 
there is concern because arafat is regarded as a menace he 
said 
south africa and israel had close ties for many years because of 
the international isolation both nations faced israel has cut 
support for south africa in recent years including economic and 
weapons assistance because of us pressure to isolate pretoria 
because of its whiteminority rule 
south africas jewish community still had close ties with israel 
and wanted south africa to remain a friend of israel whatever the 
ideological complexion of any future government goldberg said 
</TEXT>
