<TEXT>
secretary of state james a baker iii is about 
to venture into his first round of onsite african diplomacy a 
task that draws less attention than the arabisraeli dispute in the 
middle east but can be as complicated 
after a 25hour flight bakers aging us air force jet will 
land monday in namibia the newly independent former south african 
colony and he and other world figures will attend ceremonies for 
the new nation 
thats the easy part the united states during the reagan 
administration played a leading role in the establishment of 
namibia and is prepared to provide 78 million in aid next year to 
help the new country get on its feet 
as the us representative baker can take pride in his 
countrys help in ending a long and difficult guerrilla war 
but once the ceremonies are over baker may feel as if he is 
still trying to bring israelis and palestinians together 
that effort went into suspension this week amid an israeli 
government crisis over bakers formula for negotiations it could 
be months before the united states resumes its mediator role 
in africa though baker will be instantly hipdeep in the 
struggle over apartheid he has invited black activist nelson 
mandela to meet with him in windhoek the namibian capital and he 
has made arrangements for talks in cape town with president f w 
de klerk of south africa as well as black opponents of racial 
separation 
mandela who was freed by de klerk last month after spending 27 
years in prison is demanding that the bush administration cut its 
diplomatic ties to south africa and stiffen economic sanctions 
but state department policymakers would rather keep the current 
sanctions and use relations with pretoria such as bakers 
fivehour visit to cape town next thursday as leverage to steer de 
klerk into accelerating change 
de klerks freeing of mandela from prison and the legalization 
of the african national congress were viewed as positive even 
courageous steps by the bush administration but a 3year state of 
emergency still exists and there are up to 300 political prisoners 
whose release is a prerequisite to lifting us sanctions 
president bush in the euphoria over mandelas release invited 
de klerk to the white house but baker is likely to do a diplomatic 
softshoe away from the subject he is under pressure from american 
critics of apartheid to hold out for the dismantling of racial 
segregation first 
randall robinson executive director of the black lobbying group 
transafrica says the oval office carries with it a special 
meaning and that de klerk has not earned that recognition 
so baker will be walking a tightrope as he tries to nudge south 
africa toward more reform 
baker also may try some mediation between rival parties in 
angola 
he has invited president jose eduardo dos santos to see him in 
windhoek and jonas savimbi the leader of the usbacked unita 
rebel movement in zaire at the end of the week 
the united states has no relations with the angolan government 
and provides an estimated 45 million to 50 million a year in 
covert aid to savimbis guerrillas 
the 14year war settled into a stalemate after government forces 
captured part of mavinga a savimbi stronghold in southeast angola 
in late december 
diplomacy sometimes operates most effectively in a stalemate a 
negotiated settlement appears more attractive when neither side can 
gain the upper hand 
savimbi has ties to south africa and is a favorite of 
conservative members of congress dos santos has the support of 
cuban troops but about half of the 50000 who were in the country 
have withdrawn under the agreement that produced independence for 
namibia the rest are supposed to leave by next year 
the united states is alone among major western countries in not 
recognizing the angolan government despite ties to the soviet 
union and cuba and its marxist trappings the country is developing 
a private economy and exports about 75 percent of its oil to the 
united states through two american oil companies chevron and 
conoco 
last year dos santos accepted an invitation from 36 members of 
congress to visit the united states but he wanted to be received 
as a head of state which is impossible because of the lack of 
usangolan diplomatic relations 
so baker will have to try some fancy footwork on angola too 
while looking for openings to promote a peaceful solution 
</TEXT>
