<TEXT>
federal officials say theyve been unable to 
figure out how to seize khun sa the admitted opium warlord of 
burma now facing federal drugtrafficking charges 
a 10count indictment returned in december against khun sa was 
unsealed thursday as attorney general dick thornburgh announced the 
charges 
the charges stem from the largest heroin seizure in history 
1086 kilograms seized in february 1988 in bangkok thailand 
before they were to be shipped to new york 
khun sa is probably the largest heroin producer in the 
world said ed heath who until recently headed the drug 
enforcement administrations heroin desk 
the burmese government has been unable to apprehend khun sa 
after years of fighting his private army 
khun sa also is charged with importing or attempting to import 
more than 3500 pounds of heroin into new york between september 
1986 and february 1988 according to the indictment returned in 
us district court in brooklyn ny 
the indictment was kept sealed for several months while the dea 
explored every option that we could to determine if it was 
feasible to apprehend khun sa dea spokesman frank shults said 
thursday 
we thought that by watching his travel it might be possible 
to apprehend him in another country shults said we explored 
all those other possibilities and it was determined that that was 
not a feasible approach so the indictment was unsealed now 
the indictment was revealed just weeks after the state 
department announced a substantial increase in worldwide production 
of opium from which heroin is derived 
the worldwide total the department said was 4209 metric tons 
last year up from 2433 to 3308 tons in 1988 in burma alone 
opium production increased to 2625 tons last year up from 770 to 
1100 tons in 1988 
dea administrator jack lawn said the current us consumption of 
heroin is just over 5 metric tons a year it takes 10 tons of opium 
to make 1 ton of heroin 
lawn estimated that up to 45 percent of the heroin consumed in 
the united states comes from the burmese section of the golden 
triangle an area of southeast asia where thailand burma and laos 
meet khun sa is reputed to control as much as 90 percent of the 
heroin from burma 
the dea believes khun sa has been targeting americans as 
customers of his drug business for decades lawn said 
we believe that khun sa was predominantly responsible for the 
flow of heroin to our military forces in vietnam and in thailand 
during rampr rest and relaxation as a means of retaliating against 
the us forces for the damages they wrought during the war 
itself lawn said 
thornburgh denounced khun sa as the prince of death and 
sought to play down the difficulties of bringing him to trial in 
the united states 
khun sa leads the private shan united army a force estimated at 
4000 to 16000 guerrillas who have been battling the burmese 
government since 1958 when it broke a promise to allow the shan 
state to secede 
usburmese relations have been strained since us aid was cut 
off two years ago following several massacres and the installation 
of a military government 
but thornburgh said the two governments were united in their 
desire to apprehend khun sa and added he may be subject to 
delivery by his own forces if someone decides to betray him 
khun sa has offered repeatedly to abandon the drug trade if the 
united states would pay him millions of dollars a year for six to 
eight years to buy out the opium crops such an annual fee has been 
reported recently as ranging from 100 million to 300 million 
the us government has rejected such offers 
the last thing to do is to pay the extortionist lawn said 
</TEXT>
