<DOCNO> AP900316-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a rams horn sounded and a cantors 
melancholy psalms went out from the mound where 800 years ago 
today the jews of york committed mass suicide to escape an 
antisemitic mob 
it is sometimes called the english masada this most 
infamous incident of jewhatred in british history 
like the jews who killed themselves on the desert fortress of 
masada rather than fall slaves to rome the memory of york jewrys 
fate has survived through the ages still strong enough eight 
centuries later to draw several hundred jews and a handful of 
christians to a memorial service thursday at the place where it 
happened 
the service opened a fourday program of lectures concerts and 
exhibitions organized by jewish and christian groups and the city 
of york to commemorate the slaughter of march 16 1190 
no one knows exactly how many died but historians reckon the 
death toll was about 150 
the story was told in compelling detail by william of newburgh 
a contemporary historian who lived near the northeast england city 
antijewish feeling grew in england with the religious fervor of 
the crusades the attempt by european christians to win control of 
the holy land from the moslems by march 1190 york was close to 
exploding 
egged on by the local noblemen who thought they could clear 
their debts to jewish moneylenders by killing them a mob set out 
to hunt down the jews 
the jews fled to a castle where they were entitled to royal 
protection the mob surrounded the fortress the constable went out 
of the castle perhaps to reason with the crowd when he returned 
the frightened jews would not let him back in he called in the 
sheriff who ordered the door broken down 
the mob read this to mean royal assent to a pogrom while the 
jews assumed all hope was lost 
rabbi yomtob of joigny turned to his people and according to 
williams account told them we ought to prefer a glorious death 
to an infamous life for if we should fall into the hands of the 
enemy we should die according to their pleasure and amidst their 
mockery therefore let us willingly and devoutly with our own 
hands render up to him that life which the creator gave to us 
first to act was a man named josce who killed his wife and 
children yomtob then killed him then each head of family killed 
his loved ones and was in turn killed by yomtob yomtob died last 
those who chose not to die accepted the mobs offer of life if they 
accepted baptism but when they came out they too were killed 
finally the mob broke into york minster where the documents of 
their debts were kept and burned the papers in the vestry 
although the monarch of the time king richard the lionheart 
was furious and sent a senior official to mete out punishment the 
perpetrators were never caught and although jews continued to live 
in york many came to believe it was an accursed city 
that sentiment persists as reflected in lines by the northern 
english poet jon silkin the event has the frigid persistence of 
a growth in the flesh a gross tumor and a sense of such growth 
haunting the flesh of york 
today fewer than two dozen jews live in york and they are used 
to the surprised reactions they get from other jews 
ben sugar a retired economics lecturer who has lived in york 
since the 1930s says many jews believe a rabbinical edict forbids 
them to live here 
its a myth that has developed over the generations he said 
in an interview 
after lunch at a york hotel and a lecture on the massacre the 
jews walked through town to the bleak mound in the middle of a car 
park and up a flight of steep stairs 
they crowded into the circular stone cliffords tower built 
long after the massacre to listen to services conducted by 
anglican archbishop of york john habgood and rabbi norman solomon 
from birmingham 
psalms were read the cantor sang the dirge el malei 
rachamim god full of mercy and the crowd recited kaddish 
the prayer for the dead 
on this mound occurred one of the most atrocious events in 
medieval history said the rev geoffrey hunter the anglican 
chairman of the commemoration committee 
hunter blamed it on mob violence greedy noblemen and the 
churchs tragic and sad record in not only countenancing 
antisemitism but so often indeed fostering it 
may perpetrators and victims come together in forgiveness and 
in hope he said 
</TEXT>
