<TEXT>
an attorneys assurance that thrift owner 
charles h keating jr had federal regulators right where you 
want them in 1988 is being cited as new evidence that he exerted 
undue influence 
the letter strongly suggests the fix was in for the owner of 
lincoln savings and loan association said rep henry b gonzalez 
dtexas the house banking committee chairman who released it 
thursday 
margery waxman an attorney with sidley amp austin in washington 
telecopied the letter to keating on may 10 1988 to prepare him 
for a meeting with officials of the federal home loan bank board 
you have the board right where you want them and you should be 
able to reach an agreement which will completely satisfy you 
she said waxman added that she had successfully put pressure 
on m danny wall then chairman of the bank board and chief 
regulator of thrift institutions 
banking panel aides refused to say how they obtained the letter 
wall who quit earlier this month after harsh congressional 
criticism of his handling of lincoln said he had never met with 
waxman concerning keating her letter was a lawyer trying to 
justify a fee he said 
the treasury departments office of thrift supervision which 
succeeded the bank board as sampl regulator said the letter was 
riddled with errors and false conclusions 
waxmans law firm denied in a statement that it applied 
political pressure to the bank board or its employees it said the 
only pressure it exerted was advising the bank board that keating 
was considering filing a lawsuit 
the letter indicates what has been generally understood for 
some time that is there were intensive negotiations going on at 
the time with regard to a memo of understanding between lincoln and 
the bank board said leonard bickwit a washington attorney 
representing keatings holding company american continental corp 
keating is chairman of american continental owner of irvine 
califbased lincoln the thrift was seized by regulators last 
april and is expected to require the nations costliest sampl bailout 
at about 2 billion 
at the time waxman wrote keating was fighting federal efforts 
to rein in his institution bank board examiners based in san 
francisco had recommended that the government take over lincoln 
and keating had appealed to authorities in washington 
as you know i have put pressure on wall to work toward 
meeting your demands and he has so instructed his staff waxman 
wrote they all know the wednesday meeting is crucial to their 
future if they mess up this time it is all over 
wall however said i would not under any circumstances 
threaten anybody with their job that is not my character that is 
not my way of doing business 
the letter was written five days after a divided bank board 
decided to move the lincoln case from the jurisdiction of its san 
francisco office to washington and on the same day wall had a 
telephone conversation with keating 
waxman outlined what she expected to be the result of the 
meeting including a new examination of lincoln and memorandum of 
understanding between the institution and regulators which was 
executed five days later 
san francisco is finished she assured keating there is 
no going back to san francisco and nothing can be done to follow up 
their exam 
in the new exam she said nothing will be done that you 
are not aware of in advance 
also she told keating that bank board personnel will not be 
able to enforce any violation of the memorandum of understanding 
without going to the board first this will give you two 
bites at the apple before the board and in court if necessary 
gonzalez the house banking committee chairman said the letter 
tracks with amazing accuracy the actions taken by the board 
actions which were interpreted publicly as clamping down on 
lincoln 
in reality as the letter carefully explains the actions were 
to be shams designed not to punish but to allow keating an escape 
route he said 
rep jim leach of iowa a republican member of the banking 
panel said its clear from the law firms memo that keating 
had undue and unprecedented influence on the board this memo 
would appear to put wall at the center point of directing in a 
powerful if not coercive way his employees to abide by his 
decision to go easy on lincoln 
