<TEXT>
the deep political and emotional disagreement 
over abortion divided a congressional panel as it opened hearings 
into recent state restrictions on a womans right to end her 
pregnancy 
the chairman of the house panel rep don edwards dcalif 
drew opposition thursday when he refused to allow an antiabortion 
witness to show videotapes of a fetus inside the womb edwards is a 
sponsor of a bill that would write broad guarantees of abortion 
rights into federal law 
an antiabortion member rep james f sensenbrenner rwis 
challenged edwards ruling and after losing on a partyline vote 
walked out of the meeting he denounced this charade and 
accused majority democrats of gagging the witness 
edwards judiciary subcommittee on civil and constitutional 
rights held its first hearing on the socalled freedom of 
choice bill with a look at the effect of a missouri law 
restricting abortions 
the supreme court upheld that law in a ruling last year that 
energized the political debate on abortion 
appearing on a panel of abortionrights supporters a missouri 
woman and a physician testified that the restrictions have left 
some women unable to obtain safe abortions even when they face 
lifethreatening complications 
maralee dinsdale of carrollton mo described three difficult 
and unsuccessful pregnancies including a third last year when 
tests revealed she carried an anencephalic baby a fetus that had 
not developed a skull or brain and would not live long if brought 
to term and delivered 
i was denied a needed medical procedure that could save my 
life she said 
she said she also had a history of bleeding and other 
complications and decided to have an abortion because of the 
missouri law she said her doctor was denied permission to perform 
the abortion at the two hospitals where he practiced and referred 
her to a clinic not a hospital in neighboring kansas 
there mrs dinsdale said she suffered heavy bleeding and other 
complications after the abortion and was rushed to a hospital 20 
miles away where she recovered 
i was emotionally drained and scared to death but i felt i 
had no choice she said no hospital would help me my doctor 
had more or less abandoned me and i truly felt it would endanger 
my life more by carrying the baby to term in a sense for 
nothing 
the missouri law prohibits abortions from being performed at 
public hospitals bans tax dollars from being spent for 
encouraging or counseling women to have abortions and requires 
doctors to determine when possible whether a fetus of 20 or more 
weeks is capable of surviving outside the womb 
mrs dinsdale said she was denied an abortion at private 
hospitals even though the missouri law bans them only at public 
institutions 
dr howard i schwartz a kansas city mo obstetrician and 
gynecologist said that because of the law both private and public 
hospitals often refer women seeking abortions elsewhere even when 
the fetus has major abnormalities or the woman suffers diseases 
that could be lifethreatening if she remains pregnant 
the subcommittees dispute arose when a second panel of 
witnesses all abortion opponents testified 
sharleen r richard a radiologic technologist from michigan 
wanted to show examples of a new sonograph technology providing 
highquality images of the fetus at an early stage of pregnancy 
i have personally seen many women change their mind after they 
see that little baby in the womb she said 
but edwards said the subcommittee had a general rule against 
showing videotapes sensenbrenner protested the panel had no such 
rule and invited mrs richard to turn on her videotape machine and 
television when she moved to do so edwards ruled her out of order 
the subcommittee plans more hearings although sponsors have not 
decided whether to seek a vote on the bill similar hearings are 
scheduled in the senate 
