<TEXT>
jail officials cannot deny a female inmate 
visits with her lesbian lover merely because of her homosexuality 
a federal judge ruled 
the ruling from us district judge d brooks smith came on a 
lawsuit filed by the american civil liberties union on behalf of 
the prisoner identified only as jane doe 
the woman in blair county prison since may claimed she was 
denied visits with her lover even though jailhouse visits were 
permitted between heterosexual inmates and their spouses and lovers 
smith ruled wednesday that the ban was unconstitutional he 
cited a 1980 pennsylvania supreme court decision that the state 
cannot control the conduct of consenting adults in private marion 
damick a spokeswoman for the aclus pittsburgh chapter said 
thursday 
all visits at the jail in hollidaysburg take place in a room 
where prisoners and guests are separated by windows 
the lawsuit named warden gary sparks and the blair county prison 
board as codefendants during testimony before smith in december 
sparks defended the decision to prohibit the visits saying a 
prisoner identified as a homosexual could become the target of 
assaults and abuse by other inmates 
if the prison board files an appeal visits between the inmate 
and her lover would not be permitted until an appeals court rules 
