east germanys communist premier urged 
cautious steps toward reunification but a new survey today 
suggested that nearly half of all east germans favor an immediate 
joining after their first free election sunday 
i am for a united fatherland not for a hasty fatherland 
premier hans modrow told the newspaper berliner zeitung he added 
that unification should be step by step to guarantee europes peace 
a nationwide survey conducted jointly by the central institute 
for youth research and the institute for market research in leipzig 
said that 71 percent of the people are optimistic about their 
future a 10point increase since a similar poll in february 
nearly 50 percent of those questioned wanted immediate 
unification with west germany and 60 percent favored the new state 
to be militarily neutral the institutes said the institutes did 
not say how many people were polled and gave no margin of error 
among those cautious about quick unification were mostly members 
of the communist party according to the poll modrow remains the 
most popular east german politician with an approval rating of 75 
percent 
modrow praised the work of his outgoing caretaker government 
which included 13 other parties and groups he also said the former 
communists expect to be in the opposition and would make 
constructive proposals to serve the people 
modrows communistled government said thursday it has succeeded 
in pulling east germanys economy back from the brink of collapse 
the news about the economy came as candidates for the 24 parties 
and groupings made campaign appearances before sundays election 
for a new 400member parliament about 123 million east germans 
are eligible to vote 
overall the government has been able to lead the german 
democratic republic onto the way out of its crisis government 
spokesman wolfgang meyer told a news conference 
meyer assured east germans that the economy had stabilized and 
there was a light upward trend he offered no examples of which 
sectors of the economy were improving 
to some extent people have become aware of avoiding a 
headoverheels rush to unification he added 
the communists and smaller leftwing parties say citizens could 
