<TEXT>
a colorful male pheasant darts into a 
cornfield and several hens leave the grassy roadside ditch to fly 
into the blue sky over glenn kingdons farm a model for wildlife 
preservation 
five years ago you wouldnt see a pheasant nowhere kingdon 
said as he walked through rows of pine trees planted to protect the 
birds and rows of corn left to feed them 
its a lot different now 
now he sees 75 to 100 pheasants on his 420acre central 
illinois farm 40 miles east of peoria and it didnt happen by 
chance 
kingdon buys baby pheasants raises and releases them to an 
environment that includes both shelter and food in addition to 
planting trees and leaving a few rows of corn unharvested he 
limits mowing of roadside ditches and fence rows 
he was one of 168 people honored under successful farming 
magazines farming in the flyways program for providing habitat 
for waterfowl and wildlife within their agricultural operations 
these farmers have established wetlands planted windbreaks 
preserved virgin prairies and adopted other conservation practices 
sometimes at their own expense and sometimes with government 
financial help 
instead of mowing or burning we preserve natural areas to 
provide nesting spots for birds and small wildlife said cherrie 
anderson who was among those honored 
and we plant sweetcorn and leave some sunflowers standing to 
feed deer raccoons birds whatever comes 
she and her husband bernard of warwick nd farm 1000 acres 
near devils lake and devote about 300 acres in little pieces 
here and there to geese and ducks and other wildlife 
the main goal of farming in the flyways was to find out from 
farmers themselves what wildlife conservation practices and 
policies actually are working out on the land said john walter 
conservation editor for the des moinesbased magazine 
the program was announced a year ago and farmers were invited 
to send in descriptions of their conservation efforts the magazine 
selected winners and profiles of the farmers with the best ideas 
were published in the february issue 
two private conservation groups ducks unlimited inc and the 
national fish amp wildlife foundation and american cyanamid which 
makes farm chemicals cooperated in the program to provide awards 
to the farmers 
the top prize an heirloom shotgun worth an estimated 7000 
was presented to ray mccormick of vincennes ind who floods a 
112acre grain field in the fall for waterfowl and plants soybeans 
into standing wheat to encourage quail 
its one of the best examples of how to increase net return 
while conserving soil water and wildlife mccormick said the 
wheat cover crop makes excellent nesting habitat while helping 
control weeds and soil erosion 
rick van etten of a long grovebased conservation group called 
ducks unlimited said the flight index for waterfowl has dropped 
from 100 million birds in the mid1970s to about 65 million as 
land plowed for farming has replaced nesting areas for wildlife 
now he said some farmers are leading the effort to establish 
and protect wildlife habitat 
kingdon who estimates he spends less than 1000 a year on his 
pheasant program said farmers need to change their practices if 
they want to preserve wildlife for their grandchildren to enjoy 
we tore out all the fences the tree breaks and we mowed the 
roadsides like front yards he said we brought this on 
ourselves 
mrs anderson said she and her husband have done commonsense 
things and hope other farmers will follow their example 
its nothing expensive we dont have the money for that 
she said farming in the flyways publicized practical ideas that 
anybody could use 
