<TEXT>
former philippines first lady imelda marcos 
clutched the arm of her lawyer as she walked stoically into a 
manhattan courthouse today for a hearing about her racketeering 
trial which begins next week 
mrs marcos with her head held high walked up the steps of 
us district court with attorney gerald spence she did not speak 
to the crowd of photographers and reporters that lined the steps 
once inside the courtroom mrs marcos sat at the defense table 
with her lawyers she wore a black dress with a black scarf around 
her neck and held a black lace handkerchief 
at the hearing also attended by her codefendant saudi 
financier adnan khashoggi lawyers discussed with us district 
judge john keenan procedures for jury selection starting tuesday 
spence expressed concern about finding jurors who wouldnt have 
preconceived opinions about mrs marcos 
mrs marcos and her late husband have received much 
unfavorable press spence said she has been tried and 
convicted in the press 
he asked that openended questions be posed to prospective 
jurors about what they have read about mrs marcos and their 
attitudes about a reportedly wealthy notorious world leader 
keenan did not agree to any of the specific questions proposed 
by spence but assured him that he would conduct a through 
examination of prospective jurors i want a fair and impartial 
jury the judge said 
mrs marcos 60 arrived at laguardia airport on thursday on a 
commercial flight from honolulu where she has lived since she and 
her late husband left the philippines after a popular revolt in 
1986 
mrs marcos is charged with racketeering racketeering 
conspiracy mail fraud and obstruction of justice 
the indictment says she helped in the illegal transfer of more 
than 160 million allegedly embezzled from the philippine treasury 
to buy manhattan real estate it also accuses her of defrauding 
165 million from banking institutions to finance the properties 
khashoggi who will be tried for mail fraud and obstruction of 
justice is accused of helping the marcoses hide their ownership in 
the properties through false documents 
ferdinand marcos who was the central figure in the october 1988 
indictment died sept 28 in exile in hawaii the traditional 
mourning period in the philippines in which widows wear black is 
one year 
