exxon valdez skipper joseph hazelwoods 
defense asked today to have the jury sequestered during 
deliberations because of the upcoming anniversary of the tankers 
oil spill 
this raises the fear of a mistrial if the jury is exposed to 
demonstrations outside the courthouse attorney dick madson told 
superior court judge karl johnstone 
he added that jurors might be unable to avoid reading stories 
and seeing television coverage next week marking one year since the 
nations largest oil spill 
johnstone said alaska law provides that attorneys must ask for 
sequestration before a jury is sworn in unless good cause is 
shown he said you have not shown good cause and i am going 
to deny your application 
in a discussion about legal instructions to be given to the 
jury the judge said he would tell the panel members they may not 
consider hazelwoods alleged efforts to move his ship off a reef as 
evidence of recklessness 
he said testimony has shown clearly that it was impossible for 
the ship to move and thus there was no risk under the law 
he said however he would allow the prosecution to argue that 
hazelwoods efforts in turning on the engines and moving the ships 
rudder could be interpreted as evidence of his impairment by 
alcohol closing arguments to the jury were scheduled for tuesday 
hazelwoods lawyers rested their case thursday without calling 
him to testify in his criminal trial prosecutors also wrapped up 
thursday setting the stage for final arguments next week after six 
weeks of testimony over the grounding of hazelwoods tanker on a 
charted reef in prince william sound 
