capt hazelwood you have a right to testify and if you were 
to testify you would be subject to crossexamination johnstone 
said do you understand that right 
hazelwood seated at the counsel table answered yes 
is it your desire at this time not to testify asked the 
judge 
yes hazelwood responded 
it was the most the pensive balding skipper has said in public 
since his trial began 
a defendant is never required to testify in his own behalf and 
jurors are instructed to infer nothing from a decision against 
taking the stand 
hazelwood 43 returned to alaska from his home in huntington 
ny to stand trial on charges stemming from the march 24 
grounding of the exxon valdez a 987foot tanker which spilled 
nearly 11 million gallons of north slope crude oil into waters rich 
with fish and other marine life 
hazelwood is the only member of the ships crew to face criminal 
charges he is accused of a felony criminal mischief and three 
misdemeanors reckless endangerment operating a vessel while 
intoxicated and negligent discharge of oil 
if convicted on all counts he could be sentenced to 7 years in 
prison and fined 61000 
key issues addressed by 46 prosecution and 15 defense witnesses 
centered on whether hazelwood was reckless before and after the 
grounding 
they were questioned about whether the captain seemed drunk 
whether he erred in leaving the ships bridge in control of a third 
mate and whether he tried a dangerous maneuver to drive the 
stranded tanker off the reef 
the latter claim appeared moot by the end of testimony through 
defense witnesses who testified the gigantic ship was immovable 
johnstone said he probably will instruct jurors they cannot 
consider as reckless an attempt to do something that was impossible 
move the ship 
the last defense witnesses a marine salvage master and a naval 
architect agreed the ship was stuck firmly on bligh reef 
the final prosecution witness was robert mackintire captain of 
texaco tanker the brooklyn which preceded the exxon valdez into 
prince william sound several hours before the grounding 
mackintire testified he always remained on the bridge while 
going through the sound but on crossexamination added he did not 
consider it a particularly difficult area to navigate 
hazelwood was in his cabin and a third mate was at the helm when 
the exxon valdez ran aground 
