african national congress 
leaders exiled for decades will return home for groundbreaking 
talks with the white minority government april 11 president fw 
de klerk announced friday 
nelson mandela scheduled to arrive in south africa on saturday 
after a fivenation tour is expected to head the anc delegation at 
the discussions they are designed to remove obstacles to formal 
blackwhite negotiations on a new constitution 
the meeting is structured to address those things which are 
perceived to be stumbling blocks toward negotiations de 
klerk told a cape town news conference after the announcement 
he said some leaders of the ancs military wing fear arrest upon 
return to south africa and that could be one of the obstacles 
discussed at the meeting 
but de klerk also said he hoped the anc would drop its reference 
to continued armed struggle so all leaders could commit 
themselves to peaceful solutions 
there was no immediate comment from the anc the main black 
group fighting the white government the zambiabased organization 
said last month it wanted to hold preliminary talks with de klerk 
as soon as possible 
at a rally in stockholm sweden mandela repeated anc conditions 
for formal negotiations with the south african government the 
conditions include lifting of the state of emergency freeing of 
all political prisoners and repeal of repressive legislation 
during mandelas past week in sweden he and other anc leaders 
held extensive strategy discussions with anc president oliver 
tambo who is recovering from a stroke in stockholm 
mandela 71 was elected deputy president of the anc earlier 
this month during a visit to zambia the position makes him the 
effective leader of the organization while tambo recuperates 
the government has made clear that the anc would be only one of 
several blackled organizations it would invite to formal talks on 
a new constitution 
among others are leaders of south africas 10 black homelands 
such as mangosuthu buthelezi political leader of the zulus 
de klerk has met with many black leaders in south africa and he 
told reporters it will not be my first meeting with the anc 
ive already met mr mandela twice 
the relatively conservative buthelezi a proponent of 
capitalism has long been at odds with the anc over its use of 
violence and support for economic sanctions against south africa 
de klerk has as state president burnt the ruling national 
partys bridges behind him said buthelezi who arrived for a 
state visit in lusaka zambia 
bold movements he has made into the new south africa are 
irretrievable commitments to abandon apartheid and to establish a 
new and just social economic and politcal order in south africa 
he said 
de klerk also said the government would spend 380 million more 
this year to eliminate backlogs in black housing and education and 
purchase more land for settlement of blacks near the cities 
an additional 760 million will form the basis of a trust fund 
to be administered by the private sector it will be used to 
encourage donation from inside and outside south africa to improve 
blacks living conditions and their opportunities for advancement 
the anc was banned in 1960 and many anc leaders will make their 
first trip to south africa since going into exile three decades ago 
the president legalized the anc and more than 60 other 
organizations feb 2 nine days later he freed mandela who had 
been imprisoned 27 years for helping launch the anc sabotage 
campaign 
de klerk says he wants to negotiate a new constitution that will 
bring blacks into the national government but allow whites to 
maintain veto power over major policy decisions de klerk opposes a 
oneperson onevote system that the anc and other leading 
antiapartheid groups demand 
the anc announced last month it would not open formal talks on a 
new constitution until de klerk lifts the state of emergency 
de klerk said friday i would hope the governments actions 
and the influence of the total leadership in south africa 
including the anc will bring about a situation which will enable 
us to lift the state of emergency as soon as possible 
de klerk and other cabinet ministers said recently that some 
black leaders were not ready to negotiate and were instigating a 
wave of violence that has killed 300 blacks in the past six weeks 
the violence is considered the worst since the mid1980s which 
led the government to declare the state of emergency in june 1986 
