<TEXT>
the supreme court on friday raised the 
possibility it will decide by early summer the constitutionality of 
a new law making it a crime to burn the american flag 
the court partially granted a bush administration request for 
speedy consideration of the law ordering challengers of the law to 
file legal briefs by march 26 
the justices will wait until they receive those briefs before 
taking any further action in a pair of administration appeals to 
overturn lower court rulings that the law unconstitutionally 
stifles free speech 
the justice department on tuesday asked the high court to 
expedite consideration of the politically charged issue and 
schedule oral arguments as early as april 25 
while the department and president bush have expressed doubts 
about the laws constitutionality the administration filed legal 
papers urging the court to uphold the statute 
the department urged the high court to overturn rulings by two 
judges here and in seattle who declared the law unconstitutional 
the judges overvalued the narrow category of expressive 
conduct at stake and undervalued the compelling governmental 
interest that lies at the core of the statute the preservation of 
the flag as the unique symbol of our nation the department said 
conviction under the law carries a maximum oneyear jail 
sentence 
the justice department acknowledged that bush allowed the law to 
be enacted oct 28 without his signature because he questions its 
constitutionality and prefers a constitutional amendment to assure 
the same protection for the flag 
bush said he has serious doubts the law can withstand 
supreme court review and said a constitutional amendment is the 
only way to ensure that our flag is protected from desecration 
david cole a lawyer representing the defendants in both flag 
cases accused the administration of seeking expedited high court 
review so that flag burning will be an issue in this years 
campaign for house senate and state legislative seats 
he urged the court to schedule arguments in the case when it 
returns in october from its summer recess 
this is a very important constitutional question it shouldnt 
be subject to political considerations cole said 
the supreme court voting 54 in june struck down a texas law 
barring desecration or destruction of the flag the court said 
burning the american flag as a form of political protest is 
protected by the constitutions free speech guarantees 
the high courts june ruling touched off a political firestorm 
and led to enactment of the new flagprotection law 
democratic leaders in congress supported the law as an 
alternative to a constitutional amendment 
the cases are us vs eichman 891433 and us vs haggerty 
891434 
</TEXT>
