<TEXT>
when the white government and 
the african national congress meet they face three issues that 
could block the start of formal negotiations on a new constitution 
they are 
the state of emergency the anc wants it lifted president 
fw de klerk does too but says he will not do so until violence 
in black areas subsides more than 300 blacks have been killed in 
the past six weeks most in factional fighting 
political prisoners the anc says several hundred members 
convicted of politically motivated violence must be freed the 
government has refused but has been speaking to the lawyers of the 
prisoners also the government has been vague on status of anc 
exiles suspected of violence the exiles want guarantees they wont 
be prosecuted if they return 
violence the anc still endorses its guerrilla campaign 
though it poses no threat to the government the government says 
theres no justification for armed resistance now that the anc is a 
legal organization 
if agreement is reached on these obstacles the government the 
anc and several other black and white groups would likely begin 
formal talks on a constitution that would grant political rights to 
the 28million black majority 
other major issues include 
apartheid laws all black groups insist legislation 
segregating schools neighborhoods hospitals and other facilities 
be abolished the government has said there will be changes but so 
far opposes a full repeal 
voting rights black groups want oneperson onevote the 
government has said that would replace white domination with black 
domination many whites want guarantees the rights of minority 
groups will be protected de klerk envisions a system that gives 
blacks voting rights but allows whites to have veto power on major 
policy decisions 
land blacks account for more than 75 percent of south 
africas population but are restricted to 13 percent of the land 
black groups demand land redistribution 
