<TEXT>
housing starts fell 7 percent in february but 
remained well above the level of the last 11 months of 1989 the 
government reported friday analysts said the building pace cannot 
be sustained 
new homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted 
annual rate of 148 million units in february the commerce 
department said 
that followed a 247 percent jump in the warmest january on 
record the biggest increase since a 293 percent gain in july 1982 
despite being revised down from a 296 percent advance first 
reported last month 
temperatures remained above normal in february and although 
housing starts fell from januarys 159 millionunit level they 
remained higher than those of any month last year except for the 
166 million units started in january 1989 
the pace of activity in january and february is higher than we 
can expect over the course of the year said thomas holloway 
senior economist with the mortgage bankers association were 
probably borrowing a few starts from later in the year because of 
the warmer weather 
the increase in new construction was based entirely in the 
singlefamily sector which rose 51 percent to an annual rate of 
117 million units it was the highest level since a 119 
millionunit rate in january 1989 
the fact that singlefamily starts were up in february bodes 
well for activity in the coming months as mortgage interest rates 
head downward said john a tuccillo chief economist at the 
national association of realtors 
multifamily starts plummeted 35 percent to an annual rate of 
266000 after rising 40 percent the previous month 
analysts said the january pace resulted both from the weather 
and from builders desire to get construction underway in advance 
of new regulations designed to make apartments more accessible to 
the handicapped 
the new fair housing rules could add 3000 to the cost of 
multifamily units said david seiders chief economist for the 
national association of home builders 
david berson chief economist with the federal national mortgage 
association said a high vacancy rate also contributed to the 
multifamily weakness 
its almost certain to remain weak until vacancy rates come 
down berson said 
the northeast posted the biggest gain in overall starts up 244 
percent to an annual rate of 219000 units it was followed by a 
148 percent jump in the south to 604000 units 
starts in the midwest declined 29 percent to an annual rate of 
271000 units and in the west fell 24 percent to 383000 units 
applications for building permits a barometer of future housing 
activity fell 25 percent after a 268 percent gain in january the 
decline was the largest on record 
 
