<TEXT>
inflation and a revision in the pentagons 
costestimating system have pushed the price of the next generation 
of airtoair missiles to more than 14 billion air force 
officials told congress on friday 
the new estimate is 21 percent higher than the previous 
calculation 
lt gen ronald w yates also told the house armed services 
procurement subcommittee that the air force has suspended delivery 
of the amraam missile because of problems with some of the 140 
missiles it has accepted for testing 
most of the discrepancies fall into the category of quality 
workmanshiptype issues or process changes at the contractors 
yates said 
raytheon and hughes manufacture the missile 
the amraam which has been in development since 1981 is 
considered a smart missile 
the pentagon envisions that a fighter pilot would use radar to 
detect enemy aircraft at long distances and fire the 12foot 
missile the amraam would then use its own radar to hit the enemy 
missile 
the program however has had problems with cost overruns 
yates said the original cap imposed by congress on the program 
in 1984 was 7 billion but that limit was later revised to 75 
billion and then 77 billion 
adjusted for 1984 prices the new estimate of 1437 billion for 
the 24335 missiles the pentagon has planned to purchase would be 
93 billion 21 percent more than the last estimate 
the assistant air force secretary for acquisition john j 
welch said a fourth of the increased cost is due to higher prices 
for components and the rest stems from the defense departments 
change in its estimating methods 
yates also said that the air force is reexamining the total 
number of missiles it plans to buy in light of the diminshing 
soviet threat 
the air force is responsible for development and overseeing 
production of the amraam but the navy plans to purchase it as well 
