<TEXT>
the national centers for disease control is 
considering banning most us primate importations after a rare 
deadly virus turned up in monkeys in at least two laboratories 
officials said 
in a letter to about 200 primate importers in the united states 
cdc director william l roper warned the health of your workers 
may be at risk 
ebola virus the deadliest virus known to man before the 
discovery of aids was spotted in this country in november in 
three monkeys at a virginia products testing center in january an 
ebolarelated virus turned up in a monkey at a pennsylvania lab 
now in the wake of the initial reports further active 
transmission in monkeys in quarantine has been demonstrated 
roper said in his letter the warning was sent thursday to primate 
importers health officials and others 
the additional transmission has occurred at the virginia 
laboratory hazleton research of reston officials said 
at least 173 people in the united states have been in contact 
with monkeys blood or tissue from infected lots with one person 
showing ebola antibodies roper said 
about 10 percent of monkeys studied from different countries 
show signs of infection with filoviruses the family including 
ebola virus 
the primates involved are cynomolgus monkeys which account for 
about 75 percent of all primates brought to the united states 
according to officials of the atlantabased cdc about 16000 
cynomolgus monkeys were imported last year 
these data indicate a definite risk probably at a fairly low 
level of human infection in the course of ordinary handling and 
management of monkeys roper said 
cdc is considering imposing a temporary ban on the importation 
into the united states of cynomolgus monkeys he said 
atlantas yerkes regional primate center one of the nations 
leading primate research centers has 38 cynomolgus monkeys 
longtailed macaques but a ban would not affect the center too 
much said spokeswoman cathy yarbrough 
large primate research centers such as yerkes breed many of 
their own animals 
the cdc last month issued new guidelines for workers involved in 
the handling of such primates calling for 31day quarantines 
restricted access to animal holding areas in primate importation 
areas and protective clothing for all workers in direct animal 
contact 
those guidelines are now mandatory effective immediately roper 
said 
