<TEXT>
designers of the governments giant 
atomsmasher are finally preparing to buy land for the project but 
the battle for funding has just begun key backers told a 
scientists meeting friday 
the struggle to wring the first of a projected 75 billion from 
the federal budget for the superconducting super collider will move 
to the house science space and technology committee in two weeks 
committee chairman robert a roe dnj urged scientists 
educators and industry figures at the meeting here to lobby for the 
project in texas designed to study the particles that make up 
atoms 
we cant build it alone roe said in a speech at the 
international industrial symposium on the super collider we 
cant get the votes on the floor of the house alone 
the collider awarded to texas after an intense struggle among 
several states will consist of an underground loop 54 miles in 
diameter to be built south of dallas the precise location of the 
loop was revealed thursday at the symposium 
the collider would use powerful electromagnets to send streams 
of protons traveling at nearly the speed of light smashing into 
each other the collisions would produce even smaller particles 
leading to a better understanding of the nature of matter 
four other members of congress at the conference joined roe in 
urging a campaign of support 
make no mistake this is not a done deal said us rep jim 
chapman dtexas 
of the 75 billion the committee is expected to recommend 
spending on the project over approximately 10 years no more than 
5 billion should come from the federal government roe said most 
estimates put the final price tag of the super collider at 8 
billion 
the remainder would come from texas foreign contributors who 
could serve as contractors or research partners and from 
innovative financing one possibility roe said would be to lease 
some of the buildings on the campus planned to house the colliders 
staff of 3000 scientists and support workers 
critics say money spent on the super collider could be better 
used to meet concrete needs such as housing and improved education 
but supporters point to benefits of the competing cern particle 
physics project outside geneva switzerland fourteen nations 
cooperate in that project which is said to have brought better 
housing improved the job market in the area and led to inventions 
for every dollar we spend on the collider well at least 
bring back five dollars that wasnt there before roe said 
cern is a model but could become a threat if the collider isnt 
built some scientists say 
its important that you have good research opportunities for 
faculty so that we dont undergo a brain drain of us 
scientists said marvin gettner particle physics professor at 
northeastern university in boston who has worked at the swiss 
facility 
