beijing has pledged to guard human rights in hong kong and 
retain this british colonys legal and capitalistic systems for a 
halfcentury after it assumes control of hong kong in 1997 
the proposed bill of rights hong kongs first amends the 
colonial constitution to incorporate the provisions of the 
international covenant on civil and political rights 
the bill of rights as the embodiment of the covenant will be 
the benchmark by which all laws enacted in hong kong will be 
tested said secretary for constitutional affairs michael suen 
suen said it would be almost impossible and very complicated 
to repeal the bill 
however the bill was criticized by some members of the hong 
kong lawmaking legislative council 
legislator jimmy mcgregor told the governmentfunded radio hong 
kong that the draft was not in the best interest of the people he 
said it could be easily repealed by the government after 1997 
the bill allows for anyone who feels his rights have been 
violated to seek redress in any court or tribunal in the territory 
in an emergency the bill gives the government the right to take 
actions that would infringe on the civil rights convenant but 
these measures could not restrict certain basic rights such as the 
right of life or freedom of conscience and religion 
the government hopes to enact the bill in july 
it decided to consolidate all the human rights provisions from 
various ordinances into a bill of rights because of mounting 
concern in hong kong that china would renege its pledges after 1997 
confidence in those pledges has evaporated since beijings june 
34 military crackdown on the studentled chinese movement for 
democratic reforms 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

