two men arrested in a nineton cocaine 
bust described as the nations secondlargest pleaded guilty 
friday to a reduced charge of possessing less than one ounce of 
cocaine 
prosecutor ed cyganiewicz said he agreed to the plea bargain 
because he feared the state court jury might give a lenient 
sentence or even probation jurors might have been sympathetic 
because the defendants worked only as mules or laborers for 
drug kingpins who arent in custody he said 
defense attorneys welcomed the plea bargain entered in the 
middle of a trial after the prosecution rested its case based on 
the seizure of 18360 pounds of cocaine at a farm house last year 
youve got to admit theres a big difference between 18360 
pounds and one ounce said defense attorney hector villarreal 
said 
defendants hermenegildo sosa rivas 51 and guadencio garcia 
garcia 39 both mexican citizens face two to 20 years in prison 
and fined 10000 on the seconddegree felony charge 
the original firstdegree felony charge of possessing more than 
400 grams could have brought them life in prison and a 100000 
fine 
under texas law possession of less than 28 grams one ounce 
of cocaine is a seconddegree felony carrying a two to 20year 
sentence possession of more than an ounce is a firstdegree 
felony with harsher penalties that increase further if the amount 
exceeds 400 grams or about ninetenths of a pound 
texas department of public safety narcotics agents arrested sosa 
and garcia on oct 4 1989 during the siezure in harlingen in 
southern texas 
the only larger us cocaine seizure the department said was a 
20ton cache found in a los angelesarea warehouse the week before 
the prosecutor said he would ask judge darrell hester to impose 
the maximum penalty of 20 years at the sentencing scheduled for 
may 4 
defense attorney villarreal maintained that sosa and garcia took 
a job as day laborers oct 4 unaware the job was packing cocaine 
for shipment he said drug smugglers locked them in the house after 
they arrived 
the prosecutor countered that the house was unlocked and the 
men could have escaped any time or telephoned for help during the 
four hours they worked at the house 
