processing problems at the firm that analyzes them for schools a 
company official said friday 
what would take two to three weeks to process at this time of 
the year is now running four to five weeks said kathleen 
brouder director of information services at the college 
scholarship service part of the educational testing service 
the data processing center is the financial aid division of the 
college board and is the starting point for financial aid 
applications for about 3 million students every year 
the service analyzes financial aid applications which detail 
family assets and income to make sure they comply with federal 
financial aid rules and determine how much aid students should 
receive then sends the analysis to the colleges chosen by the 
students 
ms brouder said the delays were partly caused by new federal 
procedures and partly by an engineering problem several weeks ago 
in a scanner used to review applications automatically the firm 
had to switch to a slower manual process for several days while 
the scanner was repaired 
she said this is the peak time of year for financial aid 
applications when students must meet college deadlines to apply 
for aid for the coming school year 
colleges are being notified of the delays ms brouder said 
so far this year the center has received 11 million 
applications she said 
