<TEXT>
a federal judge struck down most of the 
navys program of random drug tests for 80000 civilian employees 
saying the pentagon failed to limit the practice to jobs affecting 
safety or military secrets 
us district judge d lowell jensen in a ruling made public 
friday also overturned the navys plan for drug testing any of its 
325000 civilian employees who cause an accident involving injury 
or property damage 
he said the navy failed to limit postaccident testing to 
serious accidents and gave local commanders too much authority to 
decide who would be tested 
the ruling is one of a series of decisions from lower federal 
courts on drug testing programs ordered for all federal agencies 
under president reagan in 1986 the supreme court upheld testing of 
some railway workers and customs service job applicants last year 
but didnt rule on random drug testing 
this decision proves that theyll not allow the government to 
subject federal workers to agency drug testing programs without 
adequate justifications said diane witiak of the american 
federation of government employees which represents 74000 
civilian navy workers the court is looking at individual job 
duties 
assistant us attorney george stoll said the government 
wouldnt comment friday 
jensen had blocked the entire navy civilian drug testing program 
just before it was to take effect in january his new ruling 
appeared to allow just a small fraction of the random testing 
program to go into effect though neither side in the case could 
provide any figures friday 
jensen described as overly broad the navys stated 
justifications for random tests for 80000 workers in 45 job 
categories those criteria include the workers relation to the 
operation or maintenance of equipment national security public 
health and safety protection of life and property or drug and 
alcohol rehabilitation 
the judge however upheld random testing of some of the 80000 
in certain job classes including law enforcement officers 
firefighters drivers and staff with access to topsecret 
information he also allowed testing of any navy employee based on 
reasonable suspicion of current drug use 
for example he said national security covers not only 
employees with access to topsecret information but also those 
involved in a broad range of policy and planningrelated work 
public health and safety includes lab technicians and dental 
hygienists and protection of life and property includes 
recordkeepers for rail lines 
the navy interests are so broadly defined as to describe 
virtually any duties of civilian navy employees jensen said 
only 80000 employees considered to have the most sensitive jobs 
out of the navys total of 325000 employees were targeted by the 
proposed random testing program 
in a separate ruling jensen prohibited postaccident drug 
testing of the 5800 civil service employees of the federal office 
of personnel management he said opm failed to limit the program to 
employees who actually cause accidents 
