<TEXT>
logging of virgin forests in the pacific 
northwest will probably have to be reduced further to protect the 
northern spotted owl federal officials said thursday 
the conclusion was based a on preliminary version of a report 
from scientists that was made public in an unusual meeting of the 
federal governments top four land management officials 
the chiefs of the forest service bureau of land management 
fish and wildlife service and national park service traveled to 
portland to address the issue which pits environmentalists against 
the regions vital logging industry 
lawsuits filed by environmental groups to protect spotted owl 
habitat tied up logging of vast tracts of forest land until last 
year when congress approved a compromise freeing timber sales on 
much of the land that agreement expires sept 30 
the prime habitat for the spotted owl is the regions old growth 
forests tracts of mature timber that never have been logged the 
old growth forests also account for most of the timber sold from 
federal land 
the fish and wildlife service staff has recommended the owl be 
listed as a threatened species and final decision on the listing 
is due by june 23 
f dale robertson chief of the forest service summarized some 
of the implications of the draft report produced by a committee 
assigned to plan management of federal forest land to protect the 
owls habitat 
i would say that based on what i heard this morning the 
forest service is going to have to provide some additional 
protection over and above our existing spotted owl plan 
robertson said at a news conference but how much thats still 
to be worked out 
he said that would mean a further reduction in national forest 
timber sales the mechanism by which the government allows private 
companies to log government land 
of the 1500 pairs of owls known to exist in the forests of 
oregon washington and northern california more than 90 percent 
are on land managed by one of the four interior department agencies 
represented at thursdays meeting 
there are about 7 million acres of suitable habitat for the owl 
and that would be reduced to 27 million acres by the year 2050 if 
current timbersales practices continue according to a fish and 
wildlife service report 
in addition to robertson officials at the meeting were cy 
jamison director of the bureau of land management john turner 
director of the us fish and wildlife service and jim ridenour 
head of the national park service 
the four officials declined to discuss the specifics of the 
scientists report which was being circulated for review by 
officials throughout the affected agencies it is to be made public 
april 4 at a congressional hearing in washington 
if the owl were listed as a threatened species the forest 
service and bureau of land management would be required to meet 
specific requirements for protecting its habitat before approving 
any timber sale that could hamper efforts by the two agencies to 
reach the target set in last years compromise that 77 billion 
board feet of timber be sold by sept 30 
jamison of the bureau of land management said he agreed with 
robertsons conclusions about the need for further protection for 
the owl 
robertson said the meeting was believed to be the first outside 
washington dc to include the heads of all four agencies he 
said a series of such meetings was planned and it was decided to 
make the first one in portland because the spotted owl is such a 
pressing issue 
about 150 people from a prologging organization outside the 
hotel where the federal officials met to press their case for 
increased logging 
were all very concerned about the impacts our decisions are 
going to have in the pacific northwest and in the communities 
here robertson said 
</TEXT>
