<DOCNO> AP900316-0194 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chicago mercantile exchange says it will seek 
membership approval for dualtrading restrictions that would ban 
the controversial practice in most of the mercs financial futures 
markets 
the merc said thursday it had scheduled an april 17 referendum 
in which owners of the exchanges approximately 2700 seats will 
vote on whether to ban dual trading in any contract month with 
average daily volume of 10000 contracts with certain exceptions 
if adopted the proposal would require approval of the commodity 
futures trading commission the federal regulator of the futures 
markets which is considering a complete ban on dual trading 
congress also is considering dualtrading restrictions that 
would be potentially more severe than those proposed by the merc 
although the congressional plans would allow dual trading in 
markets with a proven ability to detect fraud 
dual trading is the widespread legitimate practice among floor 
brokers at futures exchanges of trading both for their own accounts 
and their customers 
critics of the practice contend it allows brokers to defraud 
their customers by positioning themselves to profit from large 
customer orders they know will move a market an illegal activity 
known as frontrunning that prevents customers from getting the 
best possible deal 
brokers are supposed to execute any customer orders before 
trading for their own accounts 
frontrunning is one of many fraud schemes alleged by the 
government in indictments against 48 people from the merc and the 
chicago board of trade 
the exchanges have generally defended dual trading claiming it 
improves the efficiency of their markets by effectively increasing 
the pool of buyers and sellers the more players in the market 
they say the faster a customer order can be executed 
the merc proposal addresses this liquidity issue by restricting 
dual trading on a contractmonth basis instead of banning the 
practice in an entire market 
for example in the mercs standard amp poors 500 stockindex 
futures pit contracts are currently traded for delivery in march 
june september and december each contract represents the basket 
of stocks tracked by the sampp 500 index 
of the four contract months listed only two march and june 
have average daily trading volume in excess of 10000 dual trading 
would be banned in those markets but not in the september and 
december contracts 
the merc proposal would label the highvolume contract months as 
mature liquid contracts most of the mercs stockindex and 
currency futures contracts would fall into that category but its 
agricultural futures would not said spokesman andrew yemma 
in contrast a bill passed last year by the house of 
representatives would ban dual trading in any futures market with 
an annual daily volume of at least 7000 trades for all contract 
months combined that restriction would apply to nearly all of the 
markets at the merc and the board of trade 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

