<TEXT>
suddenly it seems that proxy battles are in 
with corporate predators making them the latest trend in takeovers 
but while directors of several big companies have become 
targeted for removal by dissident investors it remains to be seen 
how successful these ploys are 
the boards of lockheed corp and avon products inc face proxy 
fights by corporate suitors at their upcoming annual meetings 
meanwhile usx corp has averted a threatened proxy battle with 
carl icahn by agreeing to put his proposal for selling the 
companys steel business to a shareholder vote 
proxy fights essentially a contested shareholder election for 
control of management have regained some of their luster as other 
takeover methods such as junk bondfinanced hostile buyouts have 
lost theirs 
highrisk junk bonds were raiders tool of choice during the 
hostile takeover binge of the 1980s but with the collapse of 
several junkfinanced companies and the bonds main purveyor 
drexel burnham lambert inc some wouldbe acquirers think its 
easier to seize control through proxy battles 
investor harold simmons plans a proxy fight at lockheeds march 
29 annual meeting because hes unhappy with the current boards 
management of the defense and aerospace company he thinks he can 
do a better job of deploying its assets and cutting costs thereby 
increasing the value of his lockheed stock 
simmons who is lockheeds biggest shareholder with 19 percent 
of its stock has nominated a slate of directors that includes such 
highpowered names as former texas sen john tower and retired 
admiral elmo zumwalt jr a former member of the joint chiefs of 
staff 
at a news conference this week simmons was undaunted when a 
reporter noted that proxy fights notably icahns unsuccessful 
1988 attack on the board of texaco inc generally have had little 
success 
simmons said of icahn who is chairman of trans world airlines 
hes not basically a manager simmons and icahn both are viewed 
as corporate raiders but simmons believes he has a better track 
record after running companies like nl industries inc amalgamated 
sugar co and keystone steel and wire co 
simmons thinks that should carry some weight with lockheed 
shareholders he also believes his chances for success are better 
than icahns were at texaco because lockheed is in worse financial 
shape than the oil giant was two years ago and probably has more 
unhappy shareholders 
icahn then texacos biggest shareholder tried to unseat the 
texaco board because he thought the company wasnt doing enough to 
increase its stock price if he had won control he planned to sell 
some of its assets and distribute the proceeds to texaco 
shareholders 
texaco won the proxy battle when shareholders voted against 
icahns slate of nominees but it also undertook a restructuring 
