general development corp has agreed to plead 
guilty to federal charges in connection with an alleged scheme to 
inflate the cost of homes at the firms nine florida developments 
federal officials said today 
the plea was announced along with the unsealing of a 16count 
indictment against general development and two former executives 
the indictment was issued tuesday but not made public while 
officials discussed possible plea agreements with the defendants 
the miamibased real estate development firm agreed to plead 
guilty to one count of conspiring through certain of its officers 
to violate the federal mail fraud statute 
general development agreed to pay a fine of not more than 
500000 and agreed in principle to enter into a civil consent 
decree establishing a restitution fund for eligible homebuyers who 
purchased homes between jan 1 1982 and dec 31 1989 
charles j simons chairman president and chief executive 
officer said he was gratified that general development has been 
able to put this episode in its history behind it 
this company will be run in full compliance with all laws and 
regulations and with the highest standards of business ethics 
said simons it is clear that our house prices had gotten out of 
line with our competition and that some of our customers were 
disadvantaged 
the indictment alleged that general development sold more than 
10000 homes between 1983 and 1989 at prices exceeding fair market 
value in at least one case the home was valued at less than half 
its sale price 
also named in the indictment was gdv financial corp a general 
development subsidiary that provided mortgages and other financial 
assistance to home buyers 
former general development chairman david brown and former 
president robert ehrling were accused of fraud in the indicatment 
and were also considering plea agreements us attorney dexter 
lehtinen said 
there was no immediate comment from either man and general 
development said it did not have telephone numbers where they could 
be reached brown and ehrling were ousted from general development 
a week ago 
