neither side in the 15day greyhound bus strike is 
confident that renewed talks will produce a settlement as gunshots 
again were fired at a bus today and a striking driver was arrested 
in an earlier shooting 
federal mediators scheduled separate meetings today in tucson 
ariz with company officials and union negotiators the two sides 
were to meet facetoface saturday for the first time since 6300 
drivers and an estimated 3000 other greyhound workers walked out 
greyhound lines inc chairman fred g currey on thursday accused 
the amalgamated council of greyhound local unions of terrorism in 
connection with shooting attacks on buses and other violence 
a striking driver was charged today in the shooting monday of a 
greyhound bus in farmington conn roger d cawtra 44 of 
stratford was arrested at his home by state police and charged with 
reckless endangerment and weapons offenses police said a judge 
ordered him held on 100000 bond 
a shot fired from a passing car hit the windshield of a bus in 
phoenix early today police said greyhound spokeswoman ann wheat 
said the glass was not penetrated and no one was injured she said 
the 43 passengers on the bus bound from new york to los angeles 
were put on another bus 
currey said the violence has undermined his optimism at reaching 
a settlement 
i guess the best way to characterize my feeling is that i have 
high hopes but very low expectations currey said 
i believe these union leaders think they can win this 
strike through violence terrorism and intimidation and if they 
think that then i have very low expectations he said 
union spokesman jeffrey nelson defended union leaders though he 
acknowledged union members may be responsible for some of the 
violence 
union leaders do not believe violence will solve this 
problem he said we have repeatedly gone to union officials at 
the local level imploring them to let their own members know that 
this is not a way to solve a strike 
nelon suggested the company is positioning itself to walk out of 
the negotiations 
it takes two parties to negotiate nelson said if one 
party is not prepared to negotiate then there cant be 
negotiations 
