<TEXT>
topsyturvy weather is sending wholesale 
inflation on a rollercoaster ride so far this year with prices 
unchanged in february after a steep increase a month earlier 
a sharp drop in energy prices offset increases for other items 
and held the labor departments producer price index steady overall 
last month the government said friday 
it was the best report in six months and welcome relief after 
the huge 18 percent rise in january that increase the largest in 
15 years was driven by a record gain in energy costs and a large 
jump in food prices 
food costs rose substantially again in february particularly 
vegetables 
taken together the two months represent an annual wholesale 
inflation rate of 114 percent but many analysts believe prices 
are falling this month and predict the manufacturing slowdown will 
keep the rate for all of 1990 below the 48 percent price gain last 
year 
inflation has been capped but it hasnt been broken said 
economist robert g dederick of northern trust co in chicago 
unusual weather a deep freeze around christmas followed by 
unseasonal warmth also contributed to sharp swings in other 
economic indicators 
the federal reserve board said industrial production after 
slumping 1 percent in january bounced back 06 percent in 
february output at utilities fell and rose with the temperature a 
cutback at auto plants followed by a production rebound also 
contributed to the overall swing 
the operating rate at factories mines and utilities increased 
03 percentage point to 823 percent of capacity in february 
housing starts fell 7 percent in february returning to a more 
normal seasonally adjusted annual rate of 148 million units after 
a record leap of 247 percent a month earlier the commerce 
department said both months were warmer than usual but rain held 
back builders in february 
analysts trying to sort through the figures found little to help 
them divine the direction of the federal reserves monetary policy 
the central bank sought to avoid a recession by cutting interest 
rates over the last half of 1989 it has left shortterm rates 
unchanged since late december and now appears more interested in 
keeping rates high enough to dampen growth and consequently 
inflationary pressures 
federal reserve policy will be on hold until the direction of 
the economy becomes clearer said economist samuel d kahan of 
