<TEXT>
british industrial conglomerate btr plc offered 
164 billion friday to acquire norton co the worchesterbased 
abrasives manufacturer in an unsolicited tender offer that sent 
norton shares skyrocketing 
londonbased btr which has international operations ranging 
from building materials to sporting goods offered 75 a share for 
norton through a us subsidiary er holdings inc 
btr also threatened a proxy fight to win control of nortons 
board if the company tried to block its tender offer 
norton stock soared on news of the bid rising 1662 to 
7487 a share on the new york stock exchange 
norton spokesman francis j doherty jr said nortons board of 
directors was reviewing the offer and would inform shareholders of 
its position on the bid by march 29 
norton the worlds largest manufacturer of abrasives also 
produces ceramics plastics and chemical process products 
the company earned 858 million on sales of 153 billion in 
1989 it employs 16600 people and operates 120 plants in the 
united states and 27 in other countries 
operations of btr formerly known as british tire and rubber 
include electronics sports products and transportation under such 
companies as stewart warner in the united states borg warner in 
australia dunlop slazenger and rockwell valve 
the company had an aftertax profit of 13 billion on sales of 
113 billion last year 
btrs finance director chris bull said the company would 
finance the bid with corporate reserves and bank borrowing he said 
he did not know how much debt would be incurred but added that btr 
could cope with any repayments 
btr chairman john c cahill wrote in a letter to norton chief 
executive john h nelson that he hoped the transaction would be 
enthusiastically supported by nortons nearly 6000 
stockholders 
but he said btr would consider proposing an alternative slate of 
nominees for directors at nortons annual meeting april 26 to 
ensure that nortons board does not either through action or 
inaction deny norton stockholders the opportunity to accept our 
allcash offer 
cahills letter also included a pledge not to close any of 
nortons manufacturing facilities and to keep nortons corporate 
headquarters in worcester 
british analysts generally said btr would benefit from owning 
norton despite recent problems at the us company 
i think its a very good deal said analyst jack jones of 
the london investment firm ubsphillips and drew 
david ireland an analyst with hoare govett ltd in london said 
norton has excellent products and good market position 
but scott fulton an analyst with charterhouse tilney in london 
took a negative view everybodys been waiting for btr to make an 
acquisition and i dont think people should get excited about this 
acquisition he said 
nortons main lines of business are in decline globally and the 
company suffers from high manufacturing costs fulton said 
cahill said btr would continue its acquisitive trend in 1990 
we have a number of companies were looking at cahill said 
adding that he was targeting the united states as a prime buying 
market the united states is in vogue he said 
a number of btrs businesses were acquired including 
chicagobased stewart warner a maker of electronic and fabricated 
metal products and hardware that btr bought acquired in late 1987 
btr mounted a 18 billion hostile takeover attempt for 
britains pilkington brothers plc the giant glassmaker in late 
1986 but later dropped the bid amid a domestic political uproar 
over the move 
