<TEXT>
a year after the alaska oil spill some 
experts still point to exxon corps reaction as a virtual primer 
on how not to handle a disaster 
to be nice id say they did not distinguish themselves 
said gerald meyers former chairman and chief executive officer of 
american motors and author of a book on corporate crisis control 
when it hits the fan 
to be more blunt they screwed up he said for whatever 
reason the company appeared to be indifferent or uncaring or 
unconcerned while hundreds of sea otters and all kinds of wildlife 
were washing up on shore 
marilou hedlund managing director of the hill amp knowlton public 
relations firm in chicago said several new clients came to her 
saying in essence we dont want to have what happened to exxon 
happen to us 
reporters had trouble getting comment from exxon about the march 
24 spill and company chairman lawrence g rawls stayed away from 
the area and didnt appear before reporters until april 18 
within hours of the spill a local group volunteered to mobilize 
fishing boats to help move in equipment to keep the oil from 
spreading but in another example of what critics label exxons 
clumsiness the company never returned their call the groups 
members said by the time exxon responded with its own equipment a 
storm had moved through the area and spread the oil over a wider 
region 
the associated press called exxon asking to discuss its handling 
of spills but officials at the corporations new york 
headquarters its subsidiarys headquarters in houston and its 
bayway refinery in linden nj all declined comment 
ms hedlund and other crisis managers a burgeoning subfield of 
public relations live by a simple maxim theres no substitute for 
practice 
we do crisis training with our clients actually create an 
incredible crisis and simulated news and radio reports and see how 
they handle them she said 
ms hedlund said she also refers clients to several textbook 
examples of good crisis management including united airlines 
handling of the crash of flight 232 in iowa last summer and johnson 
amp johnsons of the nightmarish tylenol poisonings of the early 
1980s 
the key to the success of both cases was the companys 
immediate release of everything they knew and their handling of 
victims families she said 
meyers said british petroleums recent oil spill off huntington 
beach calif provides another good example 
they learned from exxon no doubt he said bps chairman 
jim ross flew there almost immediately and showed a takecharge 
attitude that was a very bad scene an oil spill right in the 
cradle of the environmental movement but they weathered the 
storm 
exxon recently halted oil loading and unloading operations at 
its only east coast refinery after three spills in two months in 
new york cityarea waters even though only one of the spills was 
directly tied to exxon property 
the shutdown illustrates exxons tension over its public image 
in the year since its tanker split open in alaskas prince william 
sound said simon trimble international oils analyst for the 
investment firm shearson lehman hutton in new york 
these days trimble said it doesnt take 10 million barrels 
of oil spilled into american waters for there to be a negative 
impact on exxon 
