<TEXT>
citicorp said friday it was reorganizing its 
commercial real estate division a move analysts linked to a rise 
in bad loans because of a downturn in the market nationwide 
under the shift citicorp is expected to deemphasize lending to 
large building projects and concentrate on real estate activities 
that generate fees for the bank such as finding investors for 
projects 
citicorp the nations largest lender among commercial banks in 
the field had 126 billion in domestic real estate loans at the 
end of 1989 nonperforming loans totaled 116 billion up from 
548 million a year earlier 
weve seen deterioration in real estate portfolios across the 
board for most large banks said richard mueller a banking 
analyst with duff amp phelps inc in chicago 
citi may be looking at not building up the loans 
outstanding he said it doesnt make sense to expand a real 
estate loan portfolio if its going to continue to demand capital 
and the returns may not be sufficient 
the real estate industry in several regions of the country has 
weakened recently because of excess capacity following expansion in 
the early and mid1980s 
overbuilding was fueled by easy credit from banks and savings 
and loans and an assumption that the market would continue 
expanding analysts said that has led to a reduction of new 
construction to allow demand to catch up with expansion 
among the hardest hit banks has been the bank of new england an 
aggressive lender during the mid1980s construction boom which 
lost 11 billion in 1989 largely due to bad loans 
along with continuing problems in the southwest tied to a 
recession there the northeast has the weakest commercial real 
estate market now analysts said florida arizona and the 
midatlantic region also have been softening 
citicorp said it remains committed to this business and we 
intend to grow and expand our franchise to deliver financial 
solutions to our clients 
the bank suggested that increasing competition from abroad also 
played a role in the reorganization foreign banks involved in a 
rising level of crossborder real estate investments have pushed 
down profit margins on international and highgrade projects 
citicorp suffered a sharp rise in nonperforming loans which are 
loans on which borrowers are not paying interest but have not yet 
defaulted in the first six months of 1989 the bank has said it 
expects an increase in the nonperforming loans in 1990 
according to published reports the restructuring will create 
two new divisions traditional real estate lending and 
feegenerating activities such as arranging sales debt and equity 
for projects 
