<TEXT>
when exxon corp returns to the oiled 
beaches of prince william sound this summer its cleanup will be 
smaller than last years and use mostly lowimpact techniques 
company officials said thursday 
lee raymond exxon corp president said at a news conference 
that winter storms had cleaned some of the gummy residue of the 
nations worst oil spill caused when the exxon valdez ran aground 
march 24 on a charted reef 
but he said a tour of the beaches a week and a half ago showed 
him that much work remains to be done beyond the 2 billion the 
company reports it has already spent on the effort 
raymond declined to say how many people would join the cleanup 
effort 
significantly less than were involved last year he said 
we would hope we could get the job done this year but thats 
based on information that wont be available until the end of 
april 
david kennedy oil spill coordinator for the national oceanic 
and atmospheric administration said earlier this week that he 
expected the exxon workforce to number in the hundreds rather than 
approach the 10000 hired last year 
noaa has suggested exxon crews pick up tarballs and oiled debris 
by hand break up asphalt and tar mats with shovels and spray 
fertilizer over the contaminated sand and gravel to promote natural 
bacteria which eat oil 
only in extreme cases should heavy machinery be brought in 
kennedy said heavy machinery such as plows can be used to turn 
over gravel to expose it to oxygen and sunlight helping the 
natural breakdown of oil 
noaa and the state have recommended the extreme measure of 
digging up the sand washing it and putting it back on beaches 
where people gather shellfish for food the agencies say that the 
shortterm damage would be overshadowed by the longterm gains 
otto harrison exxon alaska operations manager said the company 
will use cleanup techniques this summer generally less intrusive 
on the environment than the hot water and steamhose baths 
employed last year 
they range from bioremediation using the oileating 
bacteria to simply removing the oiled sediment 
to dig it up is the most intrusive thing you can do 
harrison said we dont know if the benefits are worth it 
a multiagency group is to conduct a shoreline survey in april 
and turn in a work plan by may 1 harrison said work will begin 
the first of may or as soon as weather permits harrison said 
exxons plan must be approved by coast guard adm david 
ciancaglini the federal onscene coordinator 
harrison said some sections of the shoreline most exposed to 
wind and wave action are 50 percent cleaner than they were when 
exxon cleanup workers left the coast in september 
the storms did a little better than wed hoped harrison 
said and were not through the winter yet 
the exxon valdez leaked nearly 11 million gallons of north slope 
crude oil into the clear waters of prince william sound staining 
beaches shutting down fishing seasons and killing countless birds 
and mammals 
exxon said more than 25 studies have been done over the winter 
most of which show significant shoreline improvement excellent 
water quality no missing species and no stressed animals 
fin fish are safe for consumption generally the same is true 
for shellfish except for those in the windy bay area harrison 
said 
responding to a reporters question the officials said they 
didnt plan to hire any rock polishers as the company did last 
year 
wiping rocks with rags was never a primary technique 
harrison said the material on the rocks this year is pretty 
heavy bioremediation and removal will be the primary tools 
