<TEXT>
coffee futures prices fell sharply friday on new yorks coffee 
sugar amp cocoa exchange after brazils new president announced 
sweeping economic reforms that were seen as likely to spur sales of 
brazilian coffee 
the brazilian economic package also was linked to a decline in 
soybean futures prices and to a sharp rise in sugar futures 
although analysts conceded the measures were difficult to interpret 
on other commodity markets grain futures rose oil futures were 
mostly lower precious metals advanced and livestock and meat 
futures were mostly higher 
coffee futures settled 5 cents to 6 cents lower with the 
contract for delivery in march at 8950 cents a pound 
the economic reforms outlined friday by president fernando 
collor de mello included abolishment of the brazilian coffee 
institute introduction of a new currency with freefloating 
foreign exchange rates and limits on bank withdrawals all of which 
were seen as encouraging brazilian producers and exporters to pour 
more coffee onto the world market 
brazil the largest coffee producer has been withholding coffee 
from the market which recently helped to boost coffee futures 
prices to their highest levels in eight months 
analysts said the brazilian coffee institute which administers 
the governments export and internal marketing policies is known 
to be holding a large quantity of lowquality coffee possibly as 
many as 17 million 132pound bags 
by dissolving the institute as a costcutting measure the 
government could force the agency to sell that coffee sooner that 
it would have otherwise although the beans would probably go for 
internal consumption rather than export said analyst celeste 
georkakis of cargill investor services inc 
a freefloating brazilian currency could encourage brazilian 
exporters to offer more coffee on the world market analysts said 
they said limits on bank withdrawals might prompt producers and 
exporters to sell coffee at lower prices as a way of raising cash 
analyst arthur stevenson of prudentialbache securities inc 
said that increased coffee sales was only one possible 
interpretation of the brazilian reform package 
he said the selloff in coffee futures also reflected 
disappointment about what collor de mello did not say 
the market was perhaps looking for a very constructive 
statement from the new brazilian government and that statement was 
not forthcoming stevenson said 
concerns about the new brazilian currency also prompted selling 
of soybean futures on the chicago board of trade brazil is the 
secondlargest producer of soybeans after the united states 
