<TEXT>
opec oil ministers met friday evening to 
review the groups pricing and production strategy and decide 
whether to change it in the coming months 
the meeting of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries special monitoring panel got under way amid widespread 
speculation that the cartel was unlikely to rein in current 
production anytime soon despite slackening demand and softer world 
oil prices 
opec secretarygeneral subroto said demand for the groups oil 
is expected to fall to 208 million barrels a day in coming months 
far below the 237 million barrels the cartel is estimated to be 
pumping 
the ministers met for about 90 minutes in formal session then 
adjourned the committee was expected to hold informal discussions 
in their hotel rooms on saturday 
no date was set for a final session but many doubt the 
discussions will continue beyond the weekend 
in advance of the session some ministers expressed concern that 
quotacheating by various opec members which has swelled the 
cartels production well above its target could dampen prices 
further 
prices have been slipping since early january and are expected 
to weaken further in the traditionally weak second quarter when 
seasonal factors and annual refinery maintenance reduces demand for 
crude oil 
those countries that overproduce i think they have some 
explanations surely they have some reasons behind it said 
ginandjar kartasasmita oil minister of indonesia 
we would like to hear it he said 
kuwaiti oil minister ali khalifa alsabah reflecting the unease 
about the upcoming quarter said it has three months april 
may and june i wish it had two 
the opening of the committee meeting was delayed several hours 
to give the ministers time to huddle privately in their suites at a 
luxury hotel not far from opec headquarters 
several ministers said no changes would be made in the cartels 
production and pricing guidelines for the first half of the year 
we are not suppose to take any decisions said ginandjar 
nigerian oil minister jibril aminu said the purpose of the 
meeting is to monitor production and quotas 
what decision is taken depends on the data available to us 
he said 
some were clearly worried by the cheating of such countries as 
kuwait and the united arab emirates 
mana saeed otaiba the emirates oil minister told reporters he 
would like to see both higher production and higher prices but 
acknowledged that is impossible 
when pressed to make a choice he said wed rather increase 
production until everybody is satisfied 
industry analysts put opecs output at well over 23 million 
barrels a day its supply ceiling for the januaryjune period is a 
bit more than 22 million barrels a day compared with 205 million 
barrels in the last quarter of 1989 
until recently demand in the united states and other consuming 
nations has dried up the excess supply keeping prices above the 
cartels benchmark of 18 a barrel 
but some worry that continued high production will lead to 
weaker prices in the apriljune quarter when demand tends to shrink 
with warming weather 
overproduction is a concern to us said ginandjar 
algerian oil minister sadek boussena upon arrival late 
thursday said we knew from the beginning the second quarter 
will be difficult 
iraqs minister issam abdul raheem alchalabi said demand 
will go down in the apriljune quarter thats for sure 
he predicted it would run between 21 million to 22 million barrels 
a day 
in order to keep prices up he said we will ask everybody to 
adhere to the quota and i think this will be met 
prices are not as firm as they used to be a few weeks ago 
so maybe they the overproducers will think twice about 
raising output he said 
the average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by opec 
was 1836 a barrel in the first week of march it hit 2056 a 
barrel in the first week of january 
west texas intermediate the benchmark american crude has been 
trading in the range of 20 to 21 a barrel 
in advance of the committee meeting chalabi reportedly pressed 
although unsuccessfully for a 10 percent increase in the 18 
reference price 
his suggestion like that of kuwaits ali khalifa alsabah to 
scrap the quota system will likely get an airing at the committee 
meeting the talks are designed to lay the groundwork for a 
decisionmaking conference in may 
sabah has said the quota system should be shelved because it is 
unrealistic and often ignored 
the cartel sets an overall output ceiling and then gives each 
country a quota for its production without a quota each member 
could produce freely but some of the countries now are producing 
at their limits and could not go any higher 
opec members are algeria ecuador gabon indonesia iran 
iraq kuwait libya nigeria qatar saudi arabia the united arab 
emirates and venezuela 
