<TEXT>
general development corp has agreed to plead 
guilty to a felony charge and pay up to 500000 in fines to settle 
charges it schemed to inflate home prices at its nine florida 
developments prosecutors said friday 
a 16count indictment said thousands of home buyers lured by 
slick sales pitches and florida sunshine fell prey to an elaborate 
scheme in which general development allegedly made 850 million on 
more than 11000 overpriced homes 
the indictment said the homes were sold mostly to midwest and 
northeast residents many of them recent emigrants brought to 
florida on sales junkets and blocked from learning the facts about 
the state housing market 
many of the homes sold by general development in nine 
communities between 1982 and 1989 were at least 20 percent 
overvalued compared to similar florida homes and at least one was 
listed for more than twice its estimated worth officials said 
peoples lives were devastated they were stuck with 
mortgage payments and homes valued far under what they paid said 
assistant us attorney norman moscowitz who led the twoyear 
investigation 
federal prosecutors said general development agreed to plead 
guilty to one count of mail fraud and pay the fine as part of a 
consent decree that must receive court approval 
also the homebuilder agreed to reorganize top management and 
set up a courtmonitored restitution fund that could exceed 100 
million during the next 25 years 
two former general development executives named in the fraud 
indictment are considering a plea agreement that would call for 
some jail time but the details have not been finalized us 
attorney dexter lehtinen said 
former chairman david brown and former president robert ehrling 
were making 600000 a year each before being forced out by general 
development directors march 9 they could not be reached for 
comment friday 
meanwhile the new york investment firm united capital corp 
which owns 127 percent of general development announced it plans 
to nominate six candidates to the companys board at elections in 
may 
general development which also faces several classaction 
suits has restructured its homesale policies and plans to remain 
in business said charles simons president and chief executive 
officer 
it is clear that our house prices had gotten out of line with 
our competition and that some customers were disadvantaged he 
said 
general development whose nationwide real estate holdings equal 
nearly half the size of rhode island this month has laid off about 
5500 workers about 10 percent of its work force and shut down 
sales offices in hollywood fla and boston 
in addition to 350000 lots in the nine florida developments 
general development operates a timeshare resort near disney world 
a recreational community in tennessee and 10 timeshare resorts in 
the west 
through dozens of northern sales offices and seminars general 
development pitched vacant lots or built homes only other general 
development homes were used in appraisals to back up company 
statements on the value of the properties the indictment alleged 
many customers took advantage of threeday southward ho 
subsidized trips to florida 
but general development kept potential buyers from learning 
about prices in other developments by assigning a sales 
representative to track customers constantly and screen telephone 
calls their hotel rooms the indictment alleged 
those agreeing to buy a house were told to seek a mortgage at 
gdv financial corp a general development subsidiary also named in 
the indictment general development sales officials told buyers 
that only cash and gdv mortgages were accepted as part of the 
companys onestop shopping 
chase federal savings and loan and california federal savings 
and loan two major purchasers of gdv mortgages stopped investing 
after learning of the overvalued homes since 1988 gdv sold 70 
million in mortgages to the public through drexel burnham lambert 
inc and painewebber inc 
the federal national mortgage association and the federal home 
loan mortgage corp also stopped buying gdv mortgages in 1985 
because of the companys appraisal policies 
</TEXT>
