<TEXT>
a federal judge on friday ordered drexel burnham 
lambert group inc to give creditors more information about 260 
million in bonuses paid before the firm filed for bankruptcy 
protection 
lawyers for drexel agreed to provide detailed information about 
the firms 1989 compensation and bonus payments over the weekend to 
attorneys and accountants for the official committee of unsecured 
creditors 
drexel also said it would turn over transcripts of depositions 
of drexel executives taken by the securities and exchange 
commission which is investigating the bonus payments 
creditors have questioned the timing of the bonus payments of 
196 million in cash and 64 million in securities to drexel 
exceutives in the months prior to the firms chapter 11 bankruptcy 
filing on feb 13 
sec chairman richard breeden told congress on march 2 the 
commission was investigating whether there was any was wrongdoing 
in the bonus payments which drexel said were made in december and 
january 
under federal law creditors can seek to recover payments made 
to company insiders up to one year before a bankruptcy filing 
creditors routinely seek a wide range of information about a 
companys financial condition leading up to a filing 
after drexel creditors attorney marc kirscher said the company 
was trying to impede a study of the firms financial condition 
before the chapter 11 filing drexel agreed to turn over copies of 
financial statements and auditors reports for 1988 a drexel 
spokesman said 1989 reports were not yet completed 
us bankruptcy judge howard c buschman iii said if the 
creditors committee was not satisfied with information provided by 
drexel it could raise complaints at a hearing monday 
drexel had asked that the information about the payments remain 
confidential but buschman said it would become public in court or 
through the sec 
the bonus payments were made by drexels securities subsidiary 
drexel burnham lambert inc which is not part of the bankruptcy 
case but creditors can seek information about the payments because 
they relate to the financial status of the parent firm 
also friday drexel also disclosed in court that it hoped to 
sell its 65 million investment in paramount petroleum corp for 
95 million drexel owns 53 percent of the company which is in 
bankruptcy proceedings 
buschman also resolved the first challenge by creditors to a 
planned asset sale when he allowed drexel to accept an offer for 
nearly 10 million for 141 million in highyield notes issued by 
petco a california pet supply company 
drexel underwrote the 155 percent notes due in march 1991 in a 
private placement creditors had wanted to drexel to consider other 
bids to try to get a higher price 
drexel once one of the most powerful firms on wall street 
filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection after defaulting on 
shortterm debt and failing to raise new bank credit 
under an agreement between the company and creditors three 
drexel board members are supervising the firms liquidation with 
input from creditors 
